We can write $ inom{2^{n}+i}{i}$ as $\prod_{k=1}^{i}  rac{2^{n}+k}{k}$. For any $k \leq i < 2^{n}$, the number of times $2$ divides $2^{n}+k$ is just the number of times $2$ divides $k$, so this product must have an equal number of factors of $2$ in the numerator and denominator, and therefore must be odd. Thus, as there are $2^{n}$ values of $i$ and $2^{n}$ possible values of $r$ $\pmod{2^{n+1}}$, the problem is equivalent to showing that $ inom{2^{n}+i}{i}$ is injective $\pmod{2^{n+1}}$ for $0 \leq i < 2^{n}$.

